## Your ICP

<!-- Who are you selling to? The more specific this is, the better every
     skill output becomes. If you've run /icp-definition, paste the
     summary here. -->

### Primary ICP

```
Company profile:
  Industry:     [e.g., "B2B SaaS, 50-500 employees"]
  Revenue:      [Range]
  Tech stack:   [What they typically use]
  Buying signal: [What triggers them to look for a solution like yours]

Buyer persona:
  Title:        [e.g., "VP of Engineering" or "Head of Support"]
  Reports to:   [Who they answer to]
  Day-to-day:   [What their week looks like — the workflows they live in]
  Pain:         [The specific problem that makes them search for you]
  Goal:         [What success looks like for them]
  Objections:   [What they push back on during the sales cycle]

End user persona (if different from buyer):
  Title:        [e.g., "Support agent" or "SDR"]
  Day-to-day:   [Their workflow]
  What they care about: [Speed? Ease? Power?]
```

### Anti-ICP (Who You're NOT For)

<!-- Just as important as knowing who to target. Prevents wasted effort. -->

- [Signal 1 — e.g., "Companies with fewer than 10 employees — churn rate is 3x"]
- [Signal 2 — e.g., "Teams without a dedicated ops/admin person — onboarding stalls"]
- [Signal 3]

